<br>
The point of course, is that there are two sides (at least) to each argument. Just because you are passionate about your side does not give you the right to make personal, irrational, and quite immature attacks on the people who have an opposing viewpoint, or who express that opposing viewpoint, as in reality, you have no friggin' idea what their viewpoint really is and don't care. The fact is, I shouldn't have to know the history of the FV boards to post my opinion here. If you are too sensitive about past posts, that is an issue that you need to be cognizant of, not something I feel compelled to be responsible for. The fact that an individual might hold personal disdain for another individual whose post count is lower, I must say, is a bit of a mystery to me. You have no idea who I am, how long I have been playing, what my background is, or how many other communities I am part of or run. The point of my rant is listen to yourselves, implying that I haven't been here long enough to know anything and then calling me an elitist, is well, Pot-Kettle-Black, I'll leave it at that. <br>
<br>
Many people, myself included, try to leave as much emotionalism out of our (non-rant) posts as possible (check the forum name before hopping on that one ace). The direct dissemination of information to some people implies authoritative or in some other way rigid presentation or thinking. While it does denote rigid presentation, it does not imply rigid thinking, nor authoritative sourcing. In writing, the best way to make a point is to say it. You cannot add the facial expressions (other than little happy faces <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) or body language or hand motion or inflection that would communicate to another human as fully as you could face to face. Adding excess descriptive and &quot;disclaiming&quot; not only removes from the point, but it clouds the subject matter on the whole, as well as potentially adding enough bulk to render the whole post moot - (again, this is my opinion, and if I have to say this 30 times a post, it just doesn't work for me). The other side effect of adding this type of language is that it removes stimulus for debate. Not being a PH.D. teaching, I personally prefer a discussion with some debate, although automatic gainsaying is a bit tiresome. If you don't agree with a point I have made, make a counter point. Don't just tell me I am wrong, and that I don't have a right to say anything (Cobra, you listening?). That just leads down a long road of counterproductivity, only so far down which I choose to travel. <br>
